<HL> LEISURE &amp; ARTS:
Time Off: Diversions and Excursions March 26-April 8</HL>
<DD> 03/26/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<TEXT>
      ART
   National Museum of Women in the Arts, Washington: "American Women Artists, 1830-1930" -- The first U.S. museum devoted solely to women artists opens with this exhibit of 124 paintings and sculptures from the late 19th and early 20th centuries. 
Included are works by Mary Cassatt and Georgia O'Keeffe, and lesser-known talents such as Ellen Day Hale and portraitist Cecilia Beaux. 4590 MacArthur Boulevard, N.W. April 7-June 14. 
The show travels to the Minneapolis Institute of Arts, July 5-Aug. 30; the Wadsworth Atheneum, Hartford, Conn., Sept. 19-Nov. 15; the San Diego Museum of Art, Dec. 5, 1987-Jan. 31, 1988; and the Meadows Museum, Dallas, Feb. 20-April 17, 1988. 

   Dallas Museum of Art: "A Century of Modern Sculpture: The Patsy and Raymond Nasher Collection" -- Just over 100 works by 54 artists, including Rodin, Matisse, Picasso, Brancusi and Moore. 1717 North Harwood. 
April 5-May 31. 
Selections from the show move to Washington's National Gallery of Art, June 28, 1987-Jan. 3, 1988. 

   Alexander F. Millikin Gallery, Manhattan: Birds, flowering branches, snowy landscapes and a butterfly-and-leaf-covered temptress are some of the subjects featured in a rare show of "Nihonga" -- traditional Japanese-style paintings done on paper or silk and using only natural pigments and gold hammered so thin it becomes as transparent as a ray of sun. 98 Prince St. Through April 1. 

   Diane Brown Gallery, Manhattan: "Fallen Limbs Rising" -- a collage of bronze castings and natural branches of extinct and endangered trees from the Northeast pays symbolic homage to the spirit of forests. 100 Greene St. Through April 8. 

   DANCE
   Laura Dean Dancers and Musicians: This intense, energetic troupe returns to Manhattan after an eight-year absence with a double dose of Dean -- both choreography and music. 
The program includes the New York premiere of "Magnetic," set to a dramatic synthesizer score. 
Joyce Theater, 175 Eighth Ave. (at 19th St.). 
April 7-12. (212) 242-0800. 

   Tibetan Opera, Music and Dance From Lhasa: A colorful spectacle marrying Indian drama with singing, makeup and movement styles reminiscent of Chinese opera -- Stanford, Calif. (Dinkelspiel Auditorium, Stanford University), March 26-27; Berkeley, Calif. (Zellerbach Hall, University of California at Berkeley), March 28; Mendocino, Calif. (Cotton Auditorium), March 29; Pasadena, Calif. (Beckman Auditorium, California Institute of Technology), March 31; San Diego (Mandeville Auditorium, University of California at San Diego), April 1; Santa Cruz, Calif. (Performing Arts Theatre, University of California at Santa Cruz), April 4. (212) 288-6400, ext. 286. 

   MUSIC
   Metropolitan Opera: Maria Ewing puts on basic black as novice nun Blanche de la Force in a revival of Poulenc's "The Dialogues of the Carmelites," while Marilyn Horne wields her shears wearing something more seductive for her role in Saint-Saen's "Samson et Dalila." 
Tenor Jon Vickers sings the biblical hero. 
Lincoln Center, 65th and Broadway, Manhattan. 
"Dialogues" can be seen March 27 and 30; April 4, 7 and 10. 
"Samson" runs March 28 and 31; April 3 and 8. (212) 799-3100. 

   Naoko Yoshino, a 20-year-old harpist and winner of the 1985 Ninth International Harp Contest in Israel, makes her New York debut. 
Her program includes Yuzo Toyama's "Fantasy," Spohr's "Fantasie in C minor, Op. 35," and Prokofiev's "Prelude in C Major." 
Merkin Concert Hall, Abraham Goodman House, 129 West 67th St., Manhattan. 
March 31 at 2 p.m. (212) 362-8719. 

   Houston Grand Opera: A new production of Richard Strauss's "Salome" offers Josephine Barstow, with the seven veils and sets designed by artist Jim Dine. 
Rosalind Elias is Herodias; Ingvar Wixell sings Jochanaan and John DeMain conducts. 
March 27, 28, 29 and 31; April 1 and 3. (713) 227-ARTS. 

   Opera Company of Philadelphia: Paata Burchuladze, a bass from Soviet Georgia, makes his U.S. opera debut as the crazy czar in the original 1869 version of Mussorgky's "Boris Godunov." 
The Metropolitan Opera's Max Epstein conducts. 
Academy of Music, Broad and Locust streets. 
March 30 and April 3. (215) 893-1930. 

   Chicago Opera Theater presents Britten's "The Turn of the Screw." 
Claudia Cummings, Glenn Siebert and Diane Ragains star; Steven Larsen conducts. 
Athenaeum Theater, 2936 N. Southport Ave. April 4, 5, 8, 10-12 and 15. (312) 663-0048. 

   U2: This Irish rock band's tour is one of the most eagerly awaited on the pop calendar -- Tempe, Ariz. (Arizona State University), April 2; Houston (The Summit), April 7; Las Cruces, N.M. (Pan American Center), April 10; Las Vegas (Thomas &amp; Mack Arena), April 12; San Diego (Sports Arena), April 13-14; Los Angeles (Sports Arena), April 17-18 and 20-22. 

